<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-641-967  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 641 967.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  May 22 1989 v3 n21 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Redefinition of computer crimes sought. (congressional panel)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smithmidford, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A US Congress panel on technology and law has called for sharperdefinitions of computer crime in order to fight computerbreak-ins.andP;  Despite the damage caused by the Internet worm in1988, it is unclear if any law was violated.andP;  Computer crimes thatresult in the copy or delay of data, not its loss, do not fitneatly into traditional criminal law.andP;  A bill to outlaw computerviruses and other planted programs has been introduced in theHouse of Representatives.andP;  Another problem is that plantedprograms are often hidden within other programs to make them moreeasily spread.andP;  Attendees at the hearing called for greaterattention to computer user's ethics.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer CrimesNational GovernmentLegal IssuesComputer VirusesUnited States. Congress. HouseCommitteeGovernment OfficialsEthicsSecurityLegislatureComputer Hackers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>